RX path instrumentation for CONFIG_NET_DELAYACCT.

Three insertion points:

1. net/core/dev.c, __netif_receive_skb_core() entry: stamp
   skb->delayacct_start so that the timestamp is captured as early
   as possible after the packet enters the protocol stack.

2. net/ipv4/tcp.c, tcp_recvmsg(): before skb_copy_datagram_iter()
   copies the payload to user space, call net_delayacct_rx_end() to
   accumulate the per-socket RX latency.

3. net/ipv4/udp.c, __skb_recv_udp(): same, before the skb payload is
   copied to user space.

Each modified file gains `#include <net/net-delayacct.h>` near its
existing <net/...> includes.

Complete unified diff (apply with `git apply` or `patch -p1` from the
root of a Linux 6.6 source tree).  Exact context lines may differ
between 6.6.x point releases; the helper calls must be placed as
described above.

--- a/net/core/dev.c
+++ b/net/core/dev.c
@@ -XXX,XXX @@
 #include <net/net_namespace.h>
+#include <net/net-delayacct.h>
 #include <net/dst.h>
@@ -XXX,XXX @@ static int __netif_receive_skb_core(struct sk_buff **pskb, bool pfmemalloc,
 	trace_netif_receive_skb(skb);
+	net_delayacct_rx_start(skb);
 	orig_dev = skb->dev;

--- a/net/ipv4/tcp.c
+++ b/net/ipv4/tcp.c
@@ -XXX,XXX @@
 #include <net/tcp.h>
+#include <net/net-delayacct.h>
 #include <net/xfrm.h>
@@ -XXX,XXX @@ static int tcp_recvmsg(struct sock *sk, struct msghdr *msg, size_t len,
 		if (skb->len > offset) {
+			net_delayacct_rx_end(sk, skb);
 			used = skb->len - offset;
 			if (used <= len) {

--- a/net/ipv4/udp.c
+++ b/net/ipv4/udp.c
@@ -XXX,XXX @@
 #include <net/udp.h>
+#include <net/net-delayacct.h>
 #include <net/xfrm.h>
@@ -XXX,XXX @@ struct sk_buff *__skb_recv_udp(struct sock *sk, unsigned int flags,
 			*peeked = skb->peeked;
+			net_delayacct_rx_end(sk, skb);
 			return skb;
 		}

Notes:
- The RX end helper is a no-op when skb->delayacct_start is 0
  (e.g. for loopback traffic that did not pass through
  __netif_receive_skb_core), so placing the call unconditionally is
  safe.
- IPv6 paths reuse these same TCP/UDP entry points (tcp_v6_rcv /
  udp_v6_rcv deliver into tcp_recvmsg / __skb_recv_udp), so no
  separate IPv6 instrumentation is needed.
- Fragment reassembly: only the final reassembled skb carries the
  delayacct_start timestamp, so the latency is measured end-to-end
  for the reassembled datagram.  Document this behaviour in
  docs/design.md.
